item.description:
In recent iterations of GNOME terminal, the active tab is nearly indistinguishable from the inactive ones. That makes it harder to navigate when you&rsquo;ve got a bunch of terminals open simultaneously. Fortunately, GNOME uses a modified CSS scheme to control theme appearance, and that makes it easy to highlight an active tab. Here&rsquo;s how.
Create (or edit) ~/.config/gtk-3.0/gtk.css. Add these lines:
@define-color ubuntu_orange #fb9267; TerminalWindow .notebook tab:active { background-color: shade(@ubuntu_orange,1.1); }  Then, exit all open terminals, and then open a new terminal and create a tab.

{.size-medium .wp-image-56 .alignright width=&ldquo;210px&rdquo; height=&ldquo;139px&rdquo;}
As many of you know by now, I left Genentech in September to join UC Berkeley as the Chief Scientist of the Genome Commons. I&rsquo;m part of QB3, the California Institute for Quantitative Biology (no I don&rsquo;t understand the abbreviation either).
I&rsquo;m collaborating with Steven Brenner, Jasper Rine, and Lior Pachter at Berkeley, and Robert Nussbaum and Bernie Lo at UCSF, to address the technical, scientific, clinical, and ethical opportunities associated with interpreting genomic data.
